{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"14b5df66-0224-4e6d-9b60-f26462a8b734","content":"## What happened\n\nApple's Security framework / CryptoKit **never supported DSA**. In earlier .NET versions, `DSA.Create()` on macOS silently fell back to an OpenSSL-based implementation. In .NET 11, that fallback was removed — calling `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS.\n\nThis is part of Microsoft's long-running effort to deprecate weak/legacy algorithms (DSA was already marked `[Obsolete]` with **SYSLIB0047**).\n\n## How to fix it\n\n**Option 1 — Migrate away from DSA (recommended)**\n\nDSA is a legacy algorithm with limited key sizes. Re-sign with **ECDSA** or **RSA** and update your verification code. This is the only long-term solution.\n\n**Option 2 — Use `DSAOpenSsl` directly (short-term workaround)**\n\nIf you must verify existing DSA signatures you can't re-sign, target OpenSSL explicitly on macOS:\n\n```csharp\nusing System.Security.Cryptography;\n\nDSA CreateDsa()\n{\n    if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())\n    {\n        // Requires OpenSSL installed (e.g. brew install openssl@3)\n        return new DSAOpenSsl();\n    }\n    return DSA.Create();\n}\n```\n\nYou'll need to ensure OpenSSL 3.x is available on your macOS build/run machines (e.g., `brew install openssl@3`) and that `libssl` is on the library search path.\n\n**Option 3 — Use BouncyCastle**\n\nA portable, cross-platform alternative that doesn't depend on native crypto:\n\n```csharp\n// NuGet: BouncyCastle.Cryptography\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\nvar verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\nverifier.Init(forSigning: false, publicKeyParameters);\nverifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\nbool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n```\n\n---\n\n**TL;DR**: `DSA.Create()` lost its macOS OpenSSL fallback in .NET 11. Migrate to ECDSA/RSA if possible; otherwise use `DSAOpenSsl` or BouncyCastle as a bridge.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ae5fba9a-76ee-46a0-9091-144c61170706","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a well-known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7, Microsoft began deprecating older cryptographic algorithms, and DSA specifically has been affected on macOS.\n\nHere's what happened:\n\n1. Apple's Security framework (CommonCrypto/SecKey) has never supported DSA. On macOS, .NET historically used OpenSSL (via a bundled or system copy) to provide DSA support.\n\n\n2. Microsoft marked DSA as obsolete starting with .NET 7, issuing deprecation warnings, and then in .NET 8 and later versions, calling `DSA.Create()` on macOS throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` because .NET stopped relying on OpenSSL for cryptographic operations on macOS.\n\nActually, I should clarify the timeline more carefully. The user is asking about a hypothetical .NET 10 to .NET 11 transition in 2025-2026, but I need to look at what's actually happened in recent .NET versions. DSA support on macOS has been problematic for a while—it's thrown `PlatformNotSupportedException` since around .NET 6 because Apple's native frameworks don't support DSA. Let me reconsider what the actual breaking changes have been across these versions. removed from macOS in a recent .NET version. DSA on macOS relies on OpenSSL through interop rather than Apple's native Security framework, since Apple doesn't support DSA natively. The breaking change likely involves how .NET handles or bundles OpenSSL dependencies on macOS between these versions. So on macOS desktop specifically, DSA still works through OpenSSL interop, but Apple's native crypto frameworks never supported it. Given Microsoft's pattern of deprecating DSA, it's plausible that in .NET 11 they removed the OpenSSL fallback entirely,